\begin_layout Standard
Consider the action 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:generic-scalar-action"

\end_inset

 for a generic 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 scalar field theory with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1},\cdots,\phi_{N}$
\end_inset

, reproduced here:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\left[\phi\right]=\frac{1}{2}\phi_{a}\left(-\square\delta_{ab}-m_{ab}^{2}\right)\phi_{b}-\frac{1}{3!}g_{abc}\phi_{a}\phi_{b}\phi_{c}-\frac{1}{4!}\lambda_{abcd}\phi_{a}\phi_{b}\phi_{c}\phi_{d}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The derivative term has a 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry under rotations of the fields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta\phi_{a}=iT_{ab}\phi_{b}=i\epsilon_{A}T_{ab}^{A}\phi_{b},\label{eq:field-ON-transformation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ab}=-T_{ba}$
\end_inset

 is a generator of rotations which has been expanded in the second equality
 in a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ab}^{A}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A=1,\cdots,N\left(N-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

 independent generators.
 When an explicit basis of generators is required one can take 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ab}^{jk}=i\left(\delta_{ja}\delta_{kb}-\delta_{jb}\delta_{ka}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(j,k\right)$
\end_inset

 is thought of as an (antisymmetric) multi-index.
 Note that the implicit integration convention can be maintained if 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ab}^{A}\left(x,y\right)\propto\delta\left(x-y\right)$
\end_inset

 contains a spacetime delta function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mass term in general breaks this symmetry.
 Using rotations to diagonalise 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{ab}^{2}$
\end_inset

 one finds that it consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 blocks 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{ab}^{2}=\mathrm{diag}\left(m_{1}^{2},\cdots,m_{1}^{2},m_{2}^{2},\cdots,m_{2}^{2},m_{3}^{2},\cdots,m_{k}^{2}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where each eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

-fold degenerate.
 Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{k}n_{i}=N$
\end_inset

.
 One then finds that the mass term breaks the symmetry into within-block
 symmetries 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)\to O\left(n_{1}\right)\times O\left(n_{2}\right)\times\cdots\times O\left(n_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In the case of a non-degenerate eigenvalue the corresponding group factor
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

 for the discrete symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}\to-\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This thesis focuses on continuous symmetries.
 Further, there is clearly nothing essential lost by focusing on a single
 block, since the more general case is a direct product of blocks, each
 block having a simple (in the sense of group theory) symmetry group.
 Therefore, restrict to the case of a single block where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{ab}^{2}=m^{2}\delta_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 This retains the full 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry.
 The cubic coupling transforms like a symmetric rank three tensor, but there
 is no non-trivial invariant tensor of that form.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{abc}=0$
\end_inset

 to maintain the symmetry.
 Further, the quartic coupling transforms like a symmetric rank four tensor,
 but the only possibility is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ab}\delta_{cd}+\text{permutations}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, without loss of generality one can consider the general 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetric action
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
S\left[\phi\right] & = & \frac{1}{2}\phi_{a}\left(-\square-m^{2}\right)\phi_{a}-\frac{\lambda}{4!}\left(\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right)^{2}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\phi_{a}\left(-\square\right)\phi_{a}-\frac{\lambda}{4!}\left(\phi_{a}\phi_{a}-v^{2}\right)^{2},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda v^{2}/6=-m^{2}$
\end_inset

 and the first and second lines differ by an irrelevant constant term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now the partition functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z\left[J\right]=\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\exp\left[\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(S\left[\phi\right]+J_{a}\phi_{a}\right)\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and make the change of integration variables 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:field-ON-transformation"

\end_inset

.
 As discussed above, the classical action is invariant.
 Also the functional measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]$
\end_inset

 is invariant
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Non-invariance of the functional measure arises in a number of physically
 important cases, none of which are relevant here: chiral transformations
 of fermion fields, non-linear field redefinitions, and scale and diffeomorphism
 transformations of spacetime.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thus the partition functional changes by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta Z=\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\exp\left[\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(S\left[\phi\right]+J_{a}\phi_{a}\right)\right]\frac{i}{\hbar}J_{b}\delta\phi_{b},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

but since this is simply a change of integration variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta Z=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=J_{b}T_{bc}^{A}\frac{\delta}{\delta J_{c}}Z\left[J\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which must hold independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The physical meaning of this can be understood by considering, for example,
 the quadratic term in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left[J\right]=1+\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\right)J_{a}G_{a}^{\left(1\right)}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\right)^{2}J_{a}J_{b}G_{ab}^{\left(2\right)}+\cdots$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
0 & = & J_{d}T_{dc}^{A}\frac{\delta}{\delta J_{c}}\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\right)^{2}J_{a}J_{b}G_{ab}^{\left(2\right)}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\right)^{2}\left[J_{d}T_{da}^{A}J_{b}+J_{a}J_{d}T_{db}^{A}\right]G_{ab}^{\left(2\right)}\nonumber \\
 & \propto & \left(\delta J_{a}J_{b}+J_{a}\delta J_{b}\right)G_{ab}^{\left(2\right)},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the last line 
\emph on
defines
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta J_{a}=i\epsilon_{A}T_{ab}^{A}J_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The shift above is simply that produced by a rotation of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left[J\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The fact the shift vanishes implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ab}^{\left(2\right)}$
\end_inset

 transforms like a symmetric rank two tensor under rotations, which is obvious
 in hindsight considering that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ab}^{\left(2\right)}=\left\langle \mathrm{T}_{C}\left[\phi_{a}\phi_{b}\right]\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 A similar analysis applies to each Green function with the result that
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left[J\right]$
\end_inset

 is invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 rotations of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left[J\right]=-i\hbar\ln Z\left[J\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left[J\right]$
\end_inset

 is invariant and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{a}=G_{a}^{\left(1\right)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}$
\end_inset

 both transform like vectors (i.e.
 that the relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}$
\end_inset

 is maintained under a common rotation) implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left[\varphi\right]=W\left[J\right]-J_{a}\varphi_{a}$
\end_inset

 is also invariant under rotations.
 Note that invariance holds 
\emph on
off-shell
\emph default
, that is, before equations of motion are imposed on 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 In other words the functional form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 is invariant, not just its value at solutions of the equation of motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The invariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 under rotations allows one to derive a number of identities called 
\emph on
Ward identities
\emph default
 (WIs) for the proper correlation functions.
 Start by finding the shift of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 under a rotation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta\Gamma}{\delta\varphi_{a}}i\epsilon_{A}T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b}=0.\label{eq:master-WI}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is the 
\emph on
master
\emph default
 WI.
 Since this holds off-shell one can simplify it by taking derivatives with
 respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
then
\emph default
 imposing equations of motion, which are (recall 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1piea-eom"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta\Gamma}{\delta\varphi_{a}}=-J_{a}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One can also extract the common factors 
\begin_inset Formula $i\epsilon_{A}$
\end_inset

 and define the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{W}_{a_{1}\cdots a_{m}}^{A}=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{W}_{a_{1}\cdots a_{m}}^{A}$
\end_inset

 is the left hand side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:master-WI"

\end_inset

 after taking 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 field derivatives, applying equations of motion and extracting factors.
 Proceeding this way one obtains all of the WIs, the first few of which
 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{W}^{A} & = & -J_{a}T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b},\\
\mathcal{W}_{c}^{A} & = & \Delta_{ca}^{-1}T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b}-J_{a}T_{ac}^{A},\label{eq:1PI-Delta-WI}\\
\mathcal{W}_{cd}^{A} & = & V_{dca}T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b}+\Delta_{ca}^{-1}T_{ad}^{A}+\Delta_{da}^{-1}T_{ac}^{A},\label{eq:1PI-V-WI}\\
\mathcal{W}_{cde}^{A} & = & V_{edca}^{\left(4\right)}T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b}+V_{dca}T_{ae}^{A}+V_{eca}T_{ad}^{A}+V_{eda}T_{ac}^{A},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and so on.
 These are non-trivial identities relating the (full) propagator and various
 proper vertex functions.
 The most important identities for the following development are 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1PI-Delta-WI"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1PI-V-WI"

\end_inset

, though all of them are on equal footing conceptually.
 This thesis restricts to consideration to the lowest few WIs merely for
 technical simplicity.
 The methods developed herein can be extended straightforwardly.
 Note that after 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1PI-Delta-WI"

\end_inset

 the WI do not depend explicitly on the source.
 This is useful in the discussion of linear response for symmetry improved
 effective actions in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:chap5"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The physical meaning of these identities can be best seen in simple cases.
 Setting the source to zero corresponds most often to the physical limit
 (i.e.
 when the external source is considered as a formal tool, not a physical
 quantity in and of itself).
 In this case the first WI is trivial and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1PI-Delta-WI"

\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\Delta_{ca}^{-1}T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Due to translation invariance the vacuum state has 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{a}=\text{constant}$
\end_inset

, so that this can be simplified using
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{ca}^{-1}\left(x,y\right)=\int_{p}\mathrm{e}^{-ip\left(x-y\right)}\Delta_{ca}^{-1}\left(p\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\Delta_{ca}^{-1}\left(p=0\right)T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b}=-M_{ca}^{2}T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

recalling that the zero mode of the inverse propagator is (minus) the mass
 matrix.
 Choosing without loss of generality a basis where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{b}=\left(0,\cdots,0,v\right)=v\delta_{bN}$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{ca}^{2}v=0,\ a\neq N.\label{eq:Goldstone-theorem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

There are thus two regimes: the symmetric regime where 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

, and the broken symmetry regime where 
\begin_inset Formula $v\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{ca}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 if either 
\begin_inset Formula $c,a\neq N$
\end_inset

 (it hold for both indices because 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{ca}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric).
 This identity is called 
\emph on
Goldstone's theorem
\emph default
 which says that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in any theory with a spontaneously broken continuous symmetry, each broken
 symmetry generator corresponds to a massless excitation.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There is a caveat that this only holds in more than two spacetime dimensions.
 In two or fewer dimensions spontaneous breaking of continuous symmetries
 is impossible and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

 always.
 This is discussed in more detail in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:chap4"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The massive mode is called (loosely) 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the Higgs
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 boson and the massless modes are called Goldstone bosons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the same conditions the identity 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1PI-V-WI"

\end_inset

 can be simplified by introducing the Fourier transformed three point vertex
 function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{dca}\left(x,y,z\right)=\int_{pq}\mathrm{e}^{-ip\left(x-z\right)-iq\left(y-z\right)}V_{dca}\left(p,q,-p-q\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1PI-V-WI"

\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=V_{dca}\left(p,-p,0\right)T_{aN}^{A}v+\Delta_{ca}^{-1}\left(p\right)T_{ad}^{A}+\Delta_{da}^{-1}\left(p\right)T_{ac}^{A}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting in different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 gives a slew of identities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =\Delta_{cg}^{-1}\left(p\right), &  & A=\left(g,d\right),d\neq N,\ c\neq g,d,N,\\
0 & =\Delta_{gg}^{-1}\left(p\right)-\Delta_{dd}^{-1}\left(p\right), &  & A=\left(g,d\right),c,d\neq N,\ \text{no sum on }d,g,\\
0 & =\Delta_{Na}^{-1}\left(p\right), &  & A=\left(g,g'\right),d=N,c=g',a=g,\\
0 & =V_{dcg}\left(p,-p,0\right)v, &  & A=\left(g,N\right),c,d\neq N,\\
0 & =V_{NNg}\left(p,-p,0\right)v, &  & A=\left(g,N\right),c=d=N,\\
0 & =V_{Ncg}\left(p,-p,0\right)v-\Delta_{NN}^{-1}\left(p\right)\delta_{gc}+\Delta_{cg}^{-1}\left(p\right), &  & A=\left(g,N\right),d=N,c\neq N,
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g,g'\neq N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq g'$
\end_inset

.
 The first three identities are satisfied iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{ab}^{-1}\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{ab}^{-1}=\begin{cases}
\Delta_{G}^{-1} & a=b\neq N,\\
\Delta_{H}^{-1} & a=b=N,
\end{cases}\label{eq:SSB-ansatz-Delta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{G/H}$
\end_inset

 are the Goldstone/Higgs propagators respectively, with corresponding masses
 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G/H}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last three identities have differing effects in the symmetric and broken
 symmetry regimes.
 In the symmetric regime there is 
\emph on
no constraint
\emph default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 (that is, none coming from 
\emph on
these
\emph default
 WI; the higher WI will give further constraints causing 
\begin_inset Formula $V=0$
\end_inset

), but the last identity requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{H}^{-1}=\Delta_{G}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the broken symmetry regime the first two identities are satisfied by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{abc}\left(x,y,z\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{any zero or two indices}=N,\\
V_{N}\left(x,y,z\right) & a=b=N,\\
\bar{V}\left(x;y,z\right) & a=N,\ b=c\neq N,\\
 & \text{permutations},
\end{cases}\label{eq:SSB-ansatz-Vertex}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the subtle point (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

permutations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) is that the position arguments of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{V}\left(x,y,z\right)$
\end_inset

 are 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 symmetric: by convention the first argument refers to the index which equals
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 The other two arguments are symmetric.
 The final identity requires
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{V}\left(p;-p,0\right)v-\Delta_{H}^{-1}\left(p\right)+\Delta_{G}^{-1}\left(p\right)=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To understand this physically write 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{V}\left(x,y,z\right)=-\lambda v/3\times\delta\left(x-y\right)\delta\left(x-z\right)+\delta\bar{V}$
\end_inset

 where the first term is the tree level value coming from
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{0abc}=-\frac{\lambda}{3}\left(\delta_{ab}\varphi_{c}+\delta_{ca}\varphi_{b}+\delta_{bc}\varphi_{a}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\bar{V}$
\end_inset

 represents all loop corrections to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the WI becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\frac{\lambda v^{2}}{3}+\delta\bar{V}\left(p;-p,0\right)v+m_{H}^{2}+\Sigma_{H}\left(p\right)-m_{G}^{2}-\Sigma_{G}\left(p\right)=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Matching terms of common order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
m_{H}^{2} & = & \frac{\lambda v^{2}}{3}+m_{G}^{2},\\
\delta\bar{V}\left(p;-p,0\right)v & = & \Sigma_{G}\left(p\right)-\Sigma_{H}\left(p\right).
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The first equation is the tree level relation between the masses of the
 Higgs and Goldstone bosons.
 The second equation is a relation between the vertex loop corrections with
 a soft (zero momentum) Goldstone leg and the self-energies of the Goldstone
 and Higgs bosons.
 In the symmetric regime 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}^{2}=m_{G}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{H}=\Sigma_{G}$
\end_inset

 as expected.
\end_layout

